## Multi-threaded Processing

### Single Consumer Thread Pattern (Recommended)

Use one thread for consumption, another pool for processing:

```java
class ConsumerThread extends Thread {
    private KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer;
    private BlockingQueue<ConsumerRecord<String, String>> queue;
    private volatile boolean running = true;

    public void run() {
        try {
            consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"));

            while (running) {
                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                    consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    queue.put(record);  // Non-blocking add to queue
                }
            }
        } catch (WakeupException e) {
            // Clean shutdown
        } finally {
            consumer.close();
        }
    }

    public void shutdown() {
        running = false;
        consumer.wakeup();  // ONLY thread-safe method!
    }
}

// Start consumer thread
ConsumerThread consumerThread = new ConsumerThread(consumer, queue);
consumerThread.start();

// Process records in worker thread pool
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);
while (true) {
    ConsumerRecord<String, String> record = queue.take();
    executor.submit(() -> processRecord(record));
}

// Shutdown
executor.shutdown();
consumerThread.shutdown();
executor.awaitTermination(60, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
```

**Key Points**:
- Consumer polling happens in dedicated thread
- Processing happens in separate worker threads
- Only `wakeup()` is thread-safe
- Queue ensures no concurrent access to records

### Manual Offset Commit with Thread Pool

For exactly-once semantics with worker threads:

```java
class ProcessedRecord {
    ConsumerRecord<String, String> record;
    Exception error;
}

Map<TopicPartition, Long> processedOffsets = Collections.synchronizedMap(
    new HashMap<>()
);

// Worker thread processing
executor.submit(() -> {
    try {
        String result = processRecord(record);
        processedOffsets.put(
            new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition()),
            record.offset() + 1  // Next offset to consume
        );
    } catch (Exception e) {
        // Don't update processed offset - will retry on restart
        handleError(e);
    }
});

// In consumer thread: periodically commit processed offsets
while (running) {
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
        consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
        queue.put(record);
    }

    // Commit offsets processed by workers
    if (!processedOffsets.isEmpty()) {
        Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata> toCommit =
            processedOffsets.entrySet().stream()
            .collect(Collectors.toMap(
                Map.Entry::getKey,
                e -> new OffsetAndMetadata(e.getValue())
            ));
        consumer.commitAsync(toCommit, (offsets, exception) -> {
            if (exception == null) {
                processedOffsets.clear();  // Remove committed offsets
            }
        });
    }
}
```

### Using Pause/Resume for Backpressure

```java
class ConsumerThread extends Thread {
    private BlockingQueue<ConsumerRecord<String, String>> queue;
    private static final int QUEUE_THRESHOLD = 1000;

    public void run() {
        try {
            consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"));

            while (running) {
                // Pause if queue is full
                if (queue.size() >= QUEUE_THRESHOLD) {
                    consumer.pause(consumer.assignment());
                } else if (queue.size() < QUEUE_THRESHOLD / 2) {
                    consumer.resume(consumer.paused());
                }

                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                    consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    queue.put(record);
                }
            }
        } finally {
            consumer.close();
        }
    }
}
```

**Important Considerations**:
- Pause status NOT preserved across rebalances
- Must re-apply pause logic in `onPartitionsAssigned()`
- Backpressure prevents memory exhaustion
- Coordinates consumption with processing rate

### One Consumer Per Thread Pattern

For scenarios where partition ordering is critical:

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);

// Assign 1-2 partitions per thread
List<TopicPartition> partitions = Arrays.asList(
    new TopicPartition("topic", 0),
    new TopicPartition("topic", 1)
);

for (TopicPartition partition : partitions) {
    executor.submit(() -> {
        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
        consumer.assign(Collections.singletonList(partition));

        while (running) {
            ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
            for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                processRecord(record);
            }
            consumer.commitSync();
        }

        consumer.close();
    });
}
```

**Tradeoffs**:
- **Pros**: Simple, preserves partition order, easy commits
- **Cons**: More connections, more broker load, partition count limits threads

