## Usage Patterns

### Basic Subscription with Auto-Commit

```java
Properties props = new Properties();
props.setProperty("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
props.setProperty("group.id", "my-group");
props.setProperty("enable.auto.commit", "true");
props.setProperty("auto.commit.interval.ms", "1000");
props.setProperty("key.deserializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer");
props.setProperty("value.deserializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer");

KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic1", "topic2"));

try {
    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
        for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
            System.out.printf("topic=%s, partition=%d, offset=%d, key=%s, value=%s%n",
                            record.topic(), record.partition(), record.offset(),
                            record.key(), record.value());
        }
    }
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

**When to use**:
- Exactly-once semantics not required
- At-least-once delivery acceptable
- Batch processing with lower latency requirements

### Manual Offset Management with Batch Commits

```java
props.setProperty("enable.auto.commit", "false");

KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"));

try {
    final int minBatchSize = 200;
    List<ConsumerRecord<String, String>> buffer = new ArrayList<>();

    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

        for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
            buffer.add(record);
        }

        if (buffer.size() >= minBatchSize) {
            // Process batch
            insertIntoDatabase(buffer);
            // Commit only after successful insert
            consumer.commitSync();
            buffer.clear();
        }
    }
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

**When to use**:
- Need to batch process for efficiency
- Want to avoid duplicate processing
- Database/external system handles deduplication

### Manual Partition Assignment

```java
KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);

TopicPartition partition0 = new TopicPartition("my-topic", 0);
TopicPartition partition1 = new TopicPartition("my-topic", 1);

consumer.assign(Arrays.asList(partition0, partition1));

// Restore from external state
consumer.seek(partition0, getStoredOffset("partition0"));
consumer.seek(partition1, getStoredOffset("partition1"));

try {
    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

        for (TopicPartition partition : records.partitions()) {
            for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records.records(partition)) {
                processAndStoreRecord(record);
                storeOffset(partition, record.offset() + 1);
            }
        }
    }
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

**When to use**:
- Complete control over partition assignment
- Custom offset storage outside Kafka
- Standalone consumer without group semantics

### With Rebalance Listener for External Offset Storage

```java
public class DatabaseOffsetStore implements ConsumerRebalanceListener {
    private Consumer<?, ?> consumer;
    private Database db;

    @Override
    public void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        // Save current position to database before losing partitions
        for (TopicPartition partition : partitions) {
            long offset = consumer.position(partition);
            db.saveOffset(partition, offset);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        // Load offsets from database for newly assigned partitions
        for (TopicPartition partition : partitions) {
            Long offset = db.loadOffset(partition);
            if (offset != null) {
                consumer.seek(partition, offset);
            } else {
                // First time seeing this partition
                consumer.seekToBeginning(Collections.singletonList(partition));
            }
        }
    }
}

KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"), new DatabaseOffsetStore(consumer, db));

try {
    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
        for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
            processRecord(record);
            // Offset stored in database during onPartitionsRevoked callback
        }
    }
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

**When to use**:
- Exactly-once semantics (offset + result stored atomically)
- Custom offset storage (database, file, etc.)
- Need to track processing state alongside offsets

### Replaying from Timestamp

```java
KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
consumer.assign(consumer.assignment()); // or specific partitions

// Find offsets for messages from 24 hours ago
long oneDayAgo = System.currentTimeMillis() - (24 * 60 * 60 * 1000);
Map<TopicPartition, Long> timestampsToSearch = consumer.assignment().stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(tp -> tp, tp -> oneDayAgo));

Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndTimestamp> offsets = consumer.offsetsForTimes(timestampsToSearch);

for (Map.Entry<TopicPartition, OffsetAndTimestamp> entry : offsets.entrySet()) {
    if (entry.getValue() != null) {
        consumer.seek(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue().offset());
    } else {
        // Timestamp not available (before retention period)
        consumer.seekToBeginning(Collections.singletonList(entry.getKey()));
    }
}

try {
    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
        for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
            System.out.println("Timestamp: " + new Date(record.timestamp()) +
                             ", Value: " + record.value());
        }
    }
} finally {
    consumer.close();
}
```

**When to use**:
- Time-based replay for analytics
- Recovery from specific time period
- Data exploration and debugging

